这里是一个不可避免的事实：原来的任天堂游戏男孩正在达到中年。自20089年购物中心和妈妈和流行电子产品商店的首次搬运以来，世界可能已经搬到了Sleeker，更庞大的技术。但是，在1989年回来回来。但许多开发人员正在返回Nintendo＆＃的绿色色调39; S旗舰掌握探索平台的新想法，使用经典作为模板。 ＆＃34;神奇宝贝和塞尔达是显而易见的，真正的表面级别，＆＃34; Izma，新比赛男孩游戏Deadeus的创造者说他的灵感。 ＆＃34;但后来有些人说的是有点更深。丽莎：这种游戏的痛苦，氛围和语气受到严重影响[狗狗]。像天堂的塔，一个闪光游戏男孩风格的游戏 - 叙事＆＃39; s不是强调游戏，但有一定节拍，我试图在这里匹配。＆＃34;
 目前在外套游戏中的全日制UI艺术家，Izma在游戏中与来自Magic Leap Studios的一些朋友一起制作Deadeus。他们使用GB Studio是一个免费发动机，用于建造一个标准游戏男孩的规格。 Izma一直在玩游戏男孩和＃39;在Gamemaker中的艺术风格，并发现使用GB工作室进行引人注目的肉体，以肉体齐全的全部版本。
 围绕一个年轻的男孩，在三天内避免灾难性的事件，Deadeus是一个比你的普通游戏男孩惊悚片概念更高的概念。它可以借用神奇宝贝红色和蓝色的刺激，但这种奇怪的冒险比链接＆＃39; S觉醒更甜蜜的冒险，它的11个不同的结局。
 虽然，Izma认为，游戏男孩灯头仍然滑倒了。 ＆＃34;我花了很多时间在我制作它的时候看着游戏男孩游戏的后面目录，＆＃34;他说。 ＆＃34;很多它[是什么]我＆＃39;在过去呼召和＃39;万圣节恐怖＆＃39;  - 吓得恐怖主题而不是意味着吓唬。这是100％可理解的是手持游戏和目标受众，但我也觉得那里的一点点＆＃39;＆＃34;
 在Itch.io上自由地提供，这是一个有限的Deadeus的物理运行也通过Spacebot Interactive销售，这是由Chris Beach成立的单人出版商。当海滩决定销售自己的游戏男孩幻想RPG，Dragonborne时，Spacebot开始了它。慢慢扩展到包括更多创造者，他希望建立一个扩展人们所期望的文书的图书馆，＆＃39;最古老的手持设备。
  ＆＃34;我发现它如此酷，看看为游戏男孩开发的游戏，我们从未在其一天中又回来，＆＃34;海滩通过电子邮件说。 ＆＃34;我实际上有另一场比赛，＆＃39;＆＃39; vere的其他任何不同的游戏，这是排队的。＆＃34;
     SpaceBot是＆＃39;分布游戏男孩游戏的发布商之一，仿佛我们仍然在中间的＆＃39; 90年代，使用时代的盒子，使用说明书和墨盒来完成物理包。不同的零件是有序批发，然后用手用手伸在一个人中。 
它＆＃39;所有的爱情劳动，通过了一系列年轻的渴望和易于访问的人，因为物理游戏男孩拥有一定的魔力。这些是强调收集者创造了自己版本的乙烯基;而不是野生颜色的12英寸LPS，它们＆＃39;重新制作小灰色方块，通常具有较少的储存兆字节。
 感情是SpaceBot的关键。想要成为出版商的一部分的开发人员的第一个障碍＆＃39; S Commering Boy冠军的越来越多的游戏线是激动的海滩＆＃39;兴趣。这意味着呈现给他＆＃34的东西;怀旧的兴奋和火花，＆＃34;以及对该项目的明确愿景以及它＆＃39; LL呼吁。一旦达到协议，在继续设计艺术和嵌体，运行预订，然后满足需求之前，将开始严格的错误测试过程。
    这将工作量从开发中拆开，以便在人们的手中获取购物车，并在没有中间人的情况下运作。 John Roo一直是他自己的出版商，因为他开始销售他的游戏，追捕逮捕，在Bon-Fide Pamon Boy硬件上。塞拉斯的精神继任者和警察任务游戏，Quest逮捕是一种调查的RPG，七种不同的结局，根据你作为球员的胜利方式解锁。像Deadeus一样，它是使用GB Studio制造的，但Roo不得不对发动机进行一些自定义改动来满足他的需求。
 ＆＃34;我被迫获得创意。现在，你可以建立菜单和所有这些东西，但是当我建立Quest逮捕时，我可以为我提供，＆＃34; Roo告诉我。 ＆＃34;发动机中可用的这些简单的功能暂时不存在。他们最终添加到发动机后面并使它们是正常的函数，即我在自己添加。＆＃34;
  GB Studio继续由Creator Chris Maltby-版本2.0.0更新，刚进入Beta  - 它的简单功能是游戏男孩和复古风格开发逐渐上升的核心力量。该刀具本身基于从迟到的产品上一直在网络上的软件，当时开发人员在线找到彼此时都是一个非常不同的体验。
    ＆＃34; 1999年的游戏男孩社区主要围绕着IIRC频道，GBDev，＆＃34; Super Jetpak DX Co-Developer Quang Nguyen说。 ＆＃34;我们曾经在那里闲逛，并且有一群游戏男孩发展网站被韦斯叮当联系在一起。＆＃34;
 那时，游戏男孩的颜色只有一岁，系统蓬勃发展。令人思想的家庭用品创造者分享了编码知识和通过留言板和聊天室，由Michael Hope和Pascal Felbar＆＃39; S GBDK，一个开源游戏男孩开发套件。 
使用该软件，Nguyen返回1983年＆＃39; SETPAC，ZX Spectrum Game，作为超级赛普帕克并在线发布。二十年后，在2020年的锁定后导致阮成为失业后，他和他的兄弟成为Asobi.Tech下的全日制开发人员并发布了Super Jetpak DX，这是一个改进的游戏男孩颜色版本的初始翻拍。希望和Felbar在GBDK上遗弃工作了，但许多粉丝已经复活了它作为GBDK 2020。至少有一些GB Studio基于该更新，意思是开发人员现在正在绘制那些GBDev成员的过去的聪明才智，是否他们知道它。 Nguyen仍然使用GBDK，并自从开始Super Jetpak DX开始以来分享了他的所有旧源代码和设计文件。
 GB Studio的最新迭代具有比以往更多的品种，包括通过游戏男孩接口实现点击力学的电源。进一步的边界推动是从C和装配中手动编码游戏男孩游戏的水域倾向于勇敢的开发者，实践实践，我谈到的每个开发商都符合最好的。 GB Studio和GBDK 2020等工具使您更容易将您的想法变成可播放的东西，即使您的选择较窄。
  ＆＃34;当我开始进入[游戏开发]时，人们告诉我很多你可以学习你想要的任何代码，但如果你不了解游戏的逻辑是如何工作的，它＆＃39 ;难以做到任何事情，＆＃34; Izma解释道。 ＆＃34;使用GB Studio，[by]以更远的进入级别的方式进入代码，它扼杀了困难的态度，你可以尝试并以这种方式学习。＆＃34;
 下一场比赛正在进行中罗罗＆＃39。使用在线彩色绰号复古室Roo，他计划发布和生产更多＆＃39; 90年代启发的艺术和媒体。 izma正在与其他游戏男孩有关的东西，而Asobi.Tech正在努力获得Super JetPak DX的第二次打印运行，从口袋像素设计，在延迟次数后出门。
 无论如何任何人都这样做，只要Roo，Izma和Maltby在他们的知识上传递为Nguyen和它之前的知识和第90岁以前所做的，游戏男孩游戏开发就会持续多年来。
 ＆＃34;我们站在巨人的肩膀上，＆＃34; Nguyen说。 ＆＃34;我学到的东西来自人们以前做过的东西，人们现在所做的事情是我之前所做的东西。很多人仍然使用旧工具。我们有一个gbdk 2020 discord，自＆＃39; s开源，它很高兴看到一个年轻的一代，拍摄这个旧的源代码并进一步开发它，修复了错误。＆＃34;

note_en:
Here&#39;s an unavoidable fact: the original  Nintendo Game Boy is reaching middle age. The world may have moved on to sleeker, less bulky technology since Nintendo&#39;s first portable landed in shopping malls and mom-and-pop electronics stores back in 1989. But a number of developers are returning to the green hue of Nintendo&#39;s flagship handheld to explore new ideas for the platform, using the classics as a template. &#34;  Pokémon and   Zelda are obvious, really surface level,&#34; Izma, creator of new Game Boy game   Deadeus, says of his inspirations. &#34;But then there&#39;s some that I would say are a little deeper.   Lisa: The Painful, the vibe and tone of that game heavily influenced [ Deadeus]. Things like   Tower of Heaven, a flash Game Boy-style game—the narrative&#39;s not the emphasis of the game, but there are certain beats that I tried to match here.&#34;
 Currently a full-time UI artist at  Coatsink games, Izma began making  Deadeus during a game jam with some friends from Magic Leap Studios. They used  GB Studio, a free engine for building games to the specifications of a standard Game Boy. Izma had been toying with the Game Boy&#39;s art style in  GameMaker and found using GB Studio to be compelling enough to flesh out a fuller version of what he&#39;d started.
 Centered around a young boy trying to avoid a catastrophic event over the course of three days,  Deadeus is a tad higher concept than your average Game Boy thriller. It may borrow the trappings of  Pokémon Red and  Blue, but this strange adventure is more  Donnie Darko than   Link&#39;s Awakening, featuring multiple paths to its 11 different endings.
 Izma believes some of that childlike, Game Boy lightheartedness still slipped in, though. &#34;I spent a lot of time looking at the back catalogue of the Game Boy games when I was making it,&#34; he said. &#34;A lot of it [is what] I&#39;ve called in the past &#39;Halloween horror&#39;—like horror-themed rather than meant to scare. Which is 100 percent understandable with it being a handheld game and the target audience, but I think a little bit of that&#39;s in there as well.&#34;
 Freely available on Itch.io, a limited physical run of  Deadeus was also sold through  Spacebot Interactive, a one-man publisher founded by Chris Beach. Spacebot got its start when Beach decided to sell his own Game Boy fantasy RPG,   Dragonborne. Slowly expanding to include more creators, he wants to build a library that expands what people expect from Nintendo&#39;s oldest handheld.
  &#34;I find it so cool to see games being developed for the Game Boy that we would have never had back in its day,&#34; Beach said via email. &#34;I actually have another game that&#39;s very different to anything else I&#39;ve played, which is lined up for release.&#34;
     Spacebot is one of several publishers that&#39;s distributing Game Boy games as if we were still in the mid-&#39;90s, using era-appropriate boxes, instruction manuals, and cartridges to complete the physical package. The disparate parts are ordered wholesale, then put together by hand by what is often just one person.
 It&#39;s all a labor of love, fueled by a mix of youthful longing and ease of access by people for whom the physical Game Boy holds a certain magic. These are emphatic collectors creating their own version of vinyl; instead of 12-inch LPs in wild colors, they&#39;re making small gray squares that usually have less than one megabyte of storage.
 Sentimentality is key to Spacebot. The first hurdle for developers who want to be part of the publisher&#39;s growing line of Game Boy titles is piquing Beach&#39;s interest. That means presenting something that gives him &#34;that excitement and spark of nostalgia,&#34; as well as a clear vision for the project and who it&#39;ll appeal to. Once an agreement is reached, a rigorous bug-testing process starts before moving on to designing the art and inlays, running a preorder, and then meeting demand.
    This splits the workload from development through to getting carts in people&#39;s hands, and some operate without the middleman. John Roo has been his own publisher since he started selling his game,   Quest Arrest, on bona-fide Game Boy hardware. A spiritual successor to  Sierra&#39;s  Police Quest games,  Quest Arrest is an investigative RPG with seven different endings, unlocked based on how competent you are as a player. Like  Deadeus, it was made using GB Studio, though Roo had to make some custom alterations to the engine to suit his needs.
 &#34;I was forced to get creative. Now, you can build menus and all these kinds of things, but that wasn&#39;t available to me when I was building  Quest Arrest,&#34; Roo tells me. &#34;These simple functions that are available in the engine now were nonexistent then. It was things that they ended up adding into the engine later and making them normal functions, that I was adding in myself.&#34;
  GB Studio continues to be updated by creator Chris Maltby— version 2.0.0 just entered beta—and its simple functionality has been a central force in the gradual rise in Game Boy and retro-styled development. The tool itself is based on software that has been on the web since the late &#39;90s, when developers finding each other online was a very different experience.
    &#34;The Game Boy community back in 1999 was mainly set around the IIRC channel, GBDev,&#34;   Super JetPak DX co-developer Quang Nguyen said. &#34;We used to hang out in there a lot, and there [were] a bunch of Game Boy development websites linked together by webrings.&#34;
 At that point, the Game Boy Color was only a year old, and the system was thriving. Like-minded homebrew creators shared knowledge on coding and such through message boards and chat rooms, spurred on by Michael Hope and Pascal Felbar&#39;s  GBDK, an open source Game Boy development kit.
   Using that software, Nguyen remade 1983&#39;s  Jetpac, a ZX Spectrum game, as  Super Jetpak and  released it online. Two decades later, after the 2020 lockdowns caused Nguyen to become unemployed, he and his brother became full-time developers under Asobi.tech and released  Super Jetpak DX, an improved Game Boy Color version of that initial remake. Hope and Felbar have long abandoned work on GBDK, but a number of fans have since resurrected it as  GBDK 2020. At least some of GB Studio is based on that update, meaning developers now are drawing on the past ingenuity of those GBDev members, whether they know it or not. Nguyen still uses GBDK and has shared all his old source code and design documents since beginning  Super Jetpak DX.
 The latest iteration of GB Studio features more variety than ever, including the power to implement point-and-click mechanics through the Game Boy interface. Further boundary-pushing is coming out of devs who brave the waters of manually coding Game Boy games in C and assembly, a practice practically every developer I talked to mentioned as difficult at best. Tools like GB Studio and GBDK 2020 make it easier to turn your idea into something playable, even if your options are narrower.
  &#34;People told me a lot when I started to get into [game development] that you can learn any code that you want to, but if you don&#39;t understand how the logic of a game works, it&#39;s going to be difficult to do anything,&#34; Izma explains. &#34;With GB Studio, [by] entering the code in a much more entry-level way, it scoops the difficult bit out, and you can experiment and learn that way.&#34;
 Roo&#39;s next game is well underway. Using the online moniker  The Retro Room Roo, he plans to publish and produce more &#39;90s-inspired art and media. Izma is toying with something else Game Boy-related, while Asobi.tech is working to get the second print run of  Super JetPak DX, from Pocket Pixel Design, out the door after a number of delays.
 Regardless of what anyone does, as long as Roo, Izma, and Maltby pass on their knowledge as Nguyen and those &#39;90s homebrewers did before, Game Boy game development is set to continue for many years to come.
 &#34;We stand on the shoulders of giants,&#34; Nguyen said. &#34;Stuff I learned was from stuff people did before, and the stuff that people do now is stuff that I did before. A lot of people are still using the old tools. We have a  GBDK 2020 Discord, and since it&#39;s open source, it&#39;s great to see a younger generation taking this old source code and developing it further, fixing the bugs.&#34;
